<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> Another View on SW:CCG Multiplayer<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.64)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=19054'>Wim "the Wookie" Muskee</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=19054&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 29, 2005</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> I was browsing Decktech and found myself suddenly thinking about an old version of multiplayer with SWCCG. Me and my friends had planned the event weeks in advance and the two teams (3 vs 3) were secretly making up strategies. The whole game itself lasted for one day, morning till evening, with little breaks. <br />
<br />
In this article I will present the rules by which we played a multiplayer game. The concept of multiplayer is not new, a couple of multiplayer strategies have already been described in the history of Decktech. These are the following:<br />
<br />
 - SWCCG Multiplayer? by Alex &quot;blueraider0&quot; Maslow <br />
 - SW:CCG Multiplayer by Bert &quot;Ringbearer&quot; Claessen<br />
 <br />
I&#39;ve studied them carefully before writing this article. Comparing their and my article there are similarities but also differences. The main difference between their ruleset and mine is the way players take turns and use each other&#39;s force. Conor &quot;Cobra&quot; Brace indeed points this out in his review of Alex&#39; article: &quot;... with each side trying to eliminate the other, but with the turns taken one at a time and each deck staying separate.&quot;. <br />
The similarities are based around the sharing of cards on table with your teammates. Also sharing of force-loss in drains and battle damage is possible for instance.<br />
<br />
Introduction:<br />
All players play with 60 card decks and the dark side starts the game as usual. Furthermore, the uniqueness rule still counts, also for objectives and starting effects. The uniqueness of cards more or less determines the maximum amount of players playing against each other. At a certain point, there will be no starting locations left to start with.<br />
Light and dark still fight against one another as mind against mind. The difference being that each side has more players.  Only the cards on table are shared and the effect of cards on table. The essence of this will become more clear in the following explanations.<br />
In the explanations below, I will refer to a fellow player, this can also be fellow players. I&#39;m consistent in the use of male fellow players. With that of course I&#39;m not suggesting that there are no female players, only very few.<br />
<br />
Taking Turns:<br />
Dark and light take turns after each other. If, for example, you play two against two, The first dark player takes his turn, than the first light player. After that, the second dark player plays his turn and following him the second light player. After that, everyone played his or her first turn after which the cycle starts again.<br />
<br />
The Cards:<br />
All the cards on table interact with each other as they would do in a normal game. The difference in a multiplayer game is the prescence of two decks. Two players of each side can bring cards onto the table. This way, as argued before by Alex and Bert, you can give your fellow player a needed weapon or help him win a battle.<br />
All cards of each player end up in his or her deck or lost pile. So, if cards are lost from table from whatever reason, they go to the owners lost pile.<br />
<br />
Activating:<br />
Each player activates the amount of force icons of his colour, plus one. This is indeed a lot, the result will be faster gameplay and more active, since there are two players for each side.<br />
<br />
Force Drain:<br />
A player controlling a location where the opponent does not, may force drain at that location. This rule is still valid, even for locations controlled by your fellow player&#39;s cards. Force loss caused by a force drain is directed at a side, not a player, and it can thus be divided among you and your fellow player.<br />
<br />
Battle:<br />
A battle still occurs at one location where light and dark fight each other. The player who initiates the battle draws all the necessary destiny draws, even though some cards in that battle don&#39;t belong to that player. An exception to this rule are interrupts, they may be played during the battle by your fellow player. The player playing the interrupt draws destiny for it. Also the fellow player may react if appropriate, by an interrupt.<br />
Because each player has a fixed opponent, this player draws the destinies when the other player initiates a battle, of course the fellow opponent player may help by playing interrupts. The initiator pays for all weapons, reacts etcetera except for actions caused by interrupts of his fellow player.<br />
Like a force drain, force loss as a result of battle damage can be divided among the players of a side.<br />
<br />
Movement:<br />
Each player can move all the cards of his side like normal although some cards are not of his owning. <br />
<br />
Playing, Winning and Losing:<br />
When a player&#39;s life force is depleted, that player loses. If there are still cards of that player on table, they remain there for the fellow player, who is alife to take revenge. At this point, the number of players fighting each other are not the same. However, light still followes dark and vice versa in gameplay.<br />
For practical reasons, each player chooses a personal opponent for reasons of battle. Also each player should have a clear way of identifying their own cards. <br />
A good deal of the fun is the preparation: consulting with your teammates about the strategy you&#39;re gonna take and imagination of the opponent&#39;s obliteration. This way you&#39;ll get combos of different objectives<br />
<br />
Summary:<br />
In general there is a difference between a side and a player. A player represents a side and is, together with his fellow player, responsible for the cards of his side on table. Force loss may be shared most of the time, unless it is specifically directed to one player and deployment force for instance may not be shared.<br />
I&#39;ve not given any examples of use of cards in this multiplayer mode. The rules above should be pretty clear and also you can think about it yourself given these rules. The rules are by no means holy, they are just my interpretation of how a multiplayer game should work. And, of course, dmail me if you have questions. Have fun!<br />
